WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.140
Alright, so next up, please join me in welcoming Brian Lewis who will be talking about Parallel

00:00:10.140 --> 00:00:21.440
Computing with R using foreach, future, and other packages.

00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:25.920
Alright well, people are shuffling in and out.

00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:33.000
First it goes without saying that it's a huge privilege for me to be able to hang out with

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:35.240
so many cool and interesting people.

00:00:35.240 --> 00:00:39.560
It's not, I normally don't get to hang out with cool people.

00:00:39.560 --> 00:00:44.400
So I'd really like to thank Joe, and Hadley, and JJ, and everyone at RStudio for making

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:46.400
that possible.

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:48.299
And can you all hear me okay?

00:00:48.299 --> 00:00:51.880
Because I'm going to talk really fast because I've got a ton of slides, right?

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:55.599
So, I'm kidding, but there really is a lot of slides.

00:00:55.599 --> 00:00:56.599
I'm not loud?

00:00:56.599 --> 00:00:57.599
Okay.

00:00:57.599 --> 00:01:02.279
Can you turn it up just slightly so they can hear me better, guys?

00:01:02.279 --> 00:01:04.480
Okay.

00:01:04.480 --> 00:01:05.480
Alright.

00:01:05.480 --> 00:01:11.559
Actually, wow, it's crowded.

00:01:11.559 --> 00:01:12.559
Alright let's begin.

00:01:12.559 --> 00:01:21.559
So, you're writing some R code, or maybe you're working on an R package.

00:01:21.559 --> 00:01:25.519
And your package is a super big data number crunching science package, right?

00:01:25.519 --> 00:01:30.400
So you're really, really interested and worried about performance of your code.

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:31.400
And you need to study this.

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:36.400
So maybe you pick up Pat Byrne's excellent book, The R Inferno.

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:37.959
And you learn a lot from this book.

00:01:37.959 --> 00:01:41.720
Tons of performance tips about R, and lots of other interesting nuggets about the R language.

00:01:41.720 --> 00:01:43.440
But the book kind of scares you a little bit.

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:45.599
So then you move on to Hadley's book, right?

00:01:45.599 --> 00:01:50.040
And you learn even more about the R language, and in particular about performance.

00:01:50.040 --> 00:01:54.919
And you also stroke your chin thoughtfully as you ponder all those Donald Knuth quotations

00:01:54.919 --> 00:01:58.360
in the book, right?

00:01:58.360 --> 00:02:03.239
And after studying these things for a long time, you've become expert in vectorization

00:02:03.239 --> 00:02:05.879
and bytecode compilization and all of these things.

00:02:05.879 --> 00:02:10.720
And finally, with great anticipation, you get to run your package.

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:13.919
And it runs really, really slow.

00:02:13.919 --> 00:02:14.960
It's very, very cute.

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:20.679
Your package is super cute, but it's also super, super slow, right?

00:02:20.679 --> 00:02:21.679
And then you remember, oh, wait.

00:02:21.679 --> 00:02:22.679
I've got RStudio.

00:02:22.679 --> 00:02:26.160
And they've got all these newfangled profiling tools, a profvis and other things that help

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:30.119
you look at your R codes, visualize your R code, see where it's spending all this time.

00:02:30.119 --> 00:02:34.960
So you load up your package into RStudio, and you run profvis, and you look at where

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:36.199
you're spending all their time in code.

00:02:36.199 --> 00:02:40.240
And you notice that your package is spending a lot of time in these loop-like structures

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:44.600
like L applies or maybe replicates or reduces or maps.

00:02:44.600 --> 00:02:45.639
Or is it map?

00:02:45.639 --> 00:02:46.639
Which one is it?

00:02:46.639 --> 00:02:47.639
Yeah.

00:02:47.639 --> 00:02:50.240
One of those, anyway.

00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:52.639
And then it strikes you.

00:02:52.639 --> 00:02:53.639
Of course.

00:02:53.639 --> 00:02:58.479
I spent all this crazy amount of money on my super, super fancy Mac Pro Escalade, which

00:02:58.479 --> 00:03:00.679
has got a zillion CPU cores.

00:03:00.679 --> 00:03:06.119
And all those L apply loops that I'm running are only using a single CPU.

00:03:06.119 --> 00:03:09.679
But of course, this is R. And you realize there's a package for that.

00:03:09.679 --> 00:03:10.679
The parallel package.

00:03:10.679 --> 00:03:14.360
And it even comes with R. So of course, this is what I'll use.

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:18.080
So with renewed vigor, you go back into your package, and you look at all your L applies,

00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:21.679
and you change all of the L applies to mick L applies, and you change all your maps to

00:03:21.679 --> 00:03:23.080
mick maps.

00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:27.360
All the while, you're thinking, what if McDonald's sues for trademark infringement?

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:31.600
I mean, Simon Urbanik is going to be in some serious trouble, right?

00:03:31.600 --> 00:03:34.720
And so anyway, you get all this done.

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:36.720
And finally, you're ready to run your package again.

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:38.360
And it blows your mind.

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:41.479
It's running so fast that your Mac Pro Escalade is glowing red hot.

00:03:41.479 --> 00:03:44.679
It's ripping through your data, big science code, really super fast.

00:03:44.679 --> 00:03:47.119
You've never seen R or even your Mac perform like this before.

00:03:47.119 --> 00:03:48.520
It's fantastic, right?

00:03:48.520 --> 00:03:49.919
So you tell all your friends about it.

00:03:49.919 --> 00:03:50.919
You're so excited.

00:03:50.919 --> 00:03:52.199
Everybody wants to use your package.

00:03:52.199 --> 00:03:55.199
And so your friend Jared Lander, he calls you up, and he's excited about running your

00:03:55.199 --> 00:03:56.199
package.

00:03:56.199 --> 00:03:57.199
So you give your package to Jared.

00:03:57.199 --> 00:04:01.800
And of course, Jared's using a Windows laptop, and when he runs it, it doesn't work, right?

00:04:01.800 --> 00:04:05.119
Because Windows, right?

00:04:05.119 --> 00:04:07.360
And then you think, well, yeah, wait, though.

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:13.360
Those parallel package functions, not all of them work on all the operating systems,

00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:14.360
especially Windows.

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:16.920
So you tell Jared, you know, that's not a problem, Jared.

00:04:16.920 --> 00:04:20.679
I'll just rip out some of my L applies, and I'll replace them with cluster whatever applies,

00:04:20.679 --> 00:04:21.679
right?

00:04:21.679 --> 00:04:23.160
And I'll get it all to work for you on your Windows machine.

00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:24.519
And you do that, and it works fine.

00:04:24.519 --> 00:04:28.320
Meanwhile, while you're working on that, your other friend, that's right, you've only got

00:04:28.320 --> 00:04:29.320
two friends.

00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:33.920
Your other friend, George Ostrichov, he's really excited about your package, too.

00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:37.920
And he's got, of course, he's got this super petty exit computer in his garage down there

00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:39.839
in Tennessee somewhere in the Appalachian Mountains.

00:04:39.839 --> 00:04:40.839
And he wants to run it.

00:04:40.839 --> 00:04:44.239
And you start talking about George, and you're excited to run it on such a big computer.

00:04:44.239 --> 00:04:49.640
But you realize you've got to run it using something called MPI, because George says

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:54.279
real HPC programmers use MPI, you know, whatever.

00:04:54.279 --> 00:04:55.880
But there's a package for that, too, right?

00:04:55.880 --> 00:04:56.880
There's this rmpi package.

00:04:56.880 --> 00:05:01.200
So you start rewriting your code again, and this is harder this time, because this MPI

00:05:01.200 --> 00:05:02.200
stuff is really tricky.

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:04.640
And it's like, it's taking quite a bit of while.

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:06.079
And meanwhile, this is snowballing.

00:05:06.079 --> 00:05:07.600
Other people are asking, well, what about this?

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:08.600
What about this?

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:09.600
Can I run it on that?

00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:10.600
Can I run it on that?

00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:13.959
And before long, you're losing friends, and your family's pissed off at you, because you're

00:05:13.959 --> 00:05:17.799
spending all of your time staring at an RStudio console, maintaining like 50 versions of your

00:05:17.799 --> 00:05:22.079
package for all these different parallel distributed network runtime systems, right?

00:05:22.079 --> 00:05:23.279
It's driving you crazy.

00:05:23.279 --> 00:05:24.839
And then, you know, you're neurotic, right?

00:05:24.839 --> 00:05:28.519
So you start to get really worried about this, and you're like, well, what if I lose friends

00:05:28.519 --> 00:05:29.519
over this?

00:05:29.519 --> 00:05:30.519
I might start losing sleep.

00:05:30.519 --> 00:05:31.519
And then maybe I would get depressed.

00:05:31.839 --> 00:05:32.839
I could lose my job.

00:05:32.839 --> 00:05:36.239
That would probably lead, inevitably, to a life of crime and woe.

00:05:36.239 --> 00:05:40.640
And then, finally, you have a vision of yourself as a crazy old person on a street corner ranting

00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:50.799
and raving about lazy evaluation, dark, dark, dark thoughts.

00:05:50.799 --> 00:05:55.959
This is the situation we found ourselves in in 2008.

00:05:55.959 --> 00:06:01.959
And my friend and, at the time, my colleague, Steve Weston, he looked back at this problem,

00:06:01.959 --> 00:06:06.600
and he thought, there's got to be a better way, a different way, a different approach.

00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:15.239
What if package authors and code writers could decide which parts of their program can run

00:06:15.239 --> 00:06:22.480
in parallel, and separately, later, the users of those packages decide how those codes should

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:28.079
run in parallel based on their circumstances and available resources?

00:06:28.079 --> 00:06:31.279
This is the philosophy of 4-Reach.

00:06:31.279 --> 00:06:37.679
And it's a philosophy shared by Henrik's much more recent future package.

00:06:37.679 --> 00:06:44.119
And it's a very, very important point, because we abstract away the implementation of a particular

00:06:44.119 --> 00:06:49.399
parallel portion of our code and leave that up to the user to decide at runtime how things

00:06:49.399 --> 00:06:50.399
should run.

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:57.640
Now, back in 2008, Steve made the decision to syntactically structure 4-Reach in the

00:06:57.640 --> 00:06:59.440
form of a for loop.

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:05.720
And because back then Steve was really enamored of list comprehensions and set comprehensions

00:07:05.720 --> 00:07:09.760
and all these kinds of Haskell-y things, he was really into that.

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:15.279
Speaking of Haskell, you know the reticulate package and how beautifully it integrates

00:07:15.279 --> 00:07:16.920
Python with R?

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:17.920
It's lovely, right?

00:07:17.920 --> 00:07:18.920
Have you used reticulate?

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:22.200
Wouldn't it be really cool if somebody did that with R and Haskell, right, and they could

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:23.200
call it Rascal?

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:24.200
I would really like that.

00:07:24.200 --> 00:07:26.399
That would be an excellent package.

00:07:26.399 --> 00:07:34.119
But back to 4-Reach, despite its for loop syntax, 4-Reach really kind of works like

00:07:34.119 --> 00:07:37.119
a reduce of a map.

00:07:37.119 --> 00:07:40.880
And let's make that concrete by looking at a really kind of simple contrived example.

00:07:40.880 --> 00:07:44.519
Here's a 4-Reach loop, and I'll explain each part.

00:07:44.920 --> 00:07:49.480
4-Reach is a function, and these iteration variables i and j in the blue circle, they

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:56.079
kind of play the role of any old iterator variable in a regular old for loop.

00:07:56.079 --> 00:08:01.040
And we can supply a reduction function using this .combine argument, and that can be any

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:03.880
function you want of two or more arguments.

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:06.079
And in this case, I'm just using the rbind function.

00:08:06.079 --> 00:08:09.000
And then in the purple circle, there's just a regular old R expression.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:13.119
It can be any R expression you want, and it can use those iterator variables.

00:08:13.119 --> 00:08:17.040
But in our case, we're just going to run over the unique values of i and j.

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:20.600
Each iteration of the loop is going to produce a single row data frame, and we'll pass it

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:22.119
to rbind.

00:08:22.119 --> 00:08:23.119
And if we run...

00:08:23.119 --> 00:08:28.160
But wait, there's this weird mysterious operator, dopar, that takes a function call on one side

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:30.200
and an R expression on the other.

00:08:30.200 --> 00:08:31.519
It's kind of bizarre.

00:08:31.519 --> 00:08:35.479
If we run this, well, big surprise.

00:08:35.479 --> 00:08:36.919
We have two loop iterations.

00:08:36.919 --> 00:08:40.260
Each one emits a single row of a data frame.

00:08:40.260 --> 00:08:45.059
They're passed into rbind, and our ultimate output is a two-row data frame.

00:08:45.059 --> 00:08:46.859
Rocket science.

00:08:46.859 --> 00:08:50.059
But we also get this interesting warning message from dopar.

00:08:50.059 --> 00:08:56.419
And that's dopar telling us, look, man, you didn't tell me that you could run it in parallel

00:08:56.419 --> 00:09:01.780
or you wanted to run it in parallel, so just so you know, this was run on a plain old sequential

00:09:01.780 --> 00:09:03.340
R session.

00:09:03.340 --> 00:09:04.700
And that's what dopar does.

00:09:04.700 --> 00:09:09.739
That strange operator is effectively the API of the foreach package.

00:09:10.219 --> 00:09:17.659
It's the glue that takes your R statements and variables and puts them together with

00:09:17.659 --> 00:09:23.460
various ways to run those things in parallel, like MPI or whatever.

00:09:23.460 --> 00:09:26.940
And that's the abstraction layer, the API.

00:09:26.940 --> 00:09:28.539
And so here's an example of that.

00:09:28.539 --> 00:09:35.200
A user then can register a particular parallel adapter package, in this case doparallel,

00:09:35.200 --> 00:09:39.679
with this registration function, and dopar sees that through a hidden global variable

00:09:39.679 --> 00:09:40.679
somewhere.

00:09:40.679 --> 00:09:45.919
And now the loop, without changing the code in any way, runs and gives you the same answer,

00:09:45.919 --> 00:09:47.599
but this time it's run in parallel.

00:09:47.599 --> 00:09:52.760
In this example, two separate R processes were started for each loop iteration.

00:09:52.760 --> 00:09:58.039
Their output was combined through the rbind function to give you the same result.

00:09:58.039 --> 00:10:03.760
That's the philosophy of foreach and the future package in a nutshell.

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:13.960
Thanks to Henrik's amazing work, the future package is like a new extension of this idea.

00:10:13.960 --> 00:10:15.799
It just doesn't give you any...

00:10:15.799 --> 00:10:16.799
There's no...

00:10:16.799 --> 00:10:22.440
Unlike foreach, where you have a very opinionated syntactical structure of a for loop, future

00:10:22.440 --> 00:10:26.479
package lets you do things like this using any type of R syntax that you want.

00:10:26.479 --> 00:10:30.559
You can use regular old for loops, elliplies, maps, the other map, replicate, no loop at

00:10:30.559 --> 00:10:31.559
all.

00:10:31.559 --> 00:10:32.559
You can do anything you want to do.

00:10:32.559 --> 00:10:37.320
And the cool thing is both the future package and the foreach package use magic.

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:38.799
They do.

00:10:38.799 --> 00:10:45.840
They automagically detect and make sure that lexically scoped R objects are available to

00:10:45.840 --> 00:10:47.179
the worker processes.

00:10:47.179 --> 00:10:50.679
So in this case, it's the same loop we were running before, except notice there's this

00:10:50.679 --> 00:10:55.799
K variable at the top that's not defined within the body, the expression that's in the loop.

00:10:55.799 --> 00:10:59.919
And foreach and dopar are smart enough to identify that and say, wait a minute, that

00:10:59.919 --> 00:11:01.640
worker process is going to need that value.

00:11:01.719 --> 00:11:06.760
So I make sure that it has it, even though it's defined in a lexical scope.

00:11:06.760 --> 00:11:07.760
And sure enough, it works.

00:11:07.760 --> 00:11:10.599
And that'll work if you're running it on the same computer, or if you're running it across

00:11:10.599 --> 00:11:15.400
your departmental network, or if you're using AWS to run it across the country, or even

00:11:15.400 --> 00:11:16.799
if you're running it on another planet.

00:11:16.799 --> 00:11:18.239
It'll all just work magically.

00:11:18.239 --> 00:11:21.039
It's really quite amazing.

00:11:21.039 --> 00:11:24.919
There are a few other kind of interesting things about the foreach package that are

00:11:24.919 --> 00:11:26.320
more esoteric.

00:11:26.320 --> 00:11:30.700
You can compose two foreach loops together with a composition operator, and that produces

00:11:30.979 --> 00:11:32.460
a third foreach loop.

00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:38.539
And that can be really useful for nested parallelism, to make it work, actually, in a more predictable

00:11:38.539 --> 00:11:40.500
way.

00:11:40.500 --> 00:11:45.340
And going back to the Haskell-y ideas, you can compose a foreach loop with a predicate

00:11:45.340 --> 00:11:51.780
filtering operation to produce the when function, in this case, to produce a set comprehension,

00:11:51.780 --> 00:11:54.580
a very Haskell-y kind of thing.

00:11:54.580 --> 00:11:57.580
And Steve was very much into those ideas.

00:11:57.580 --> 00:12:00.619
Let's see, where are we at?

00:12:00.659 --> 00:12:04.500
Now, again, thanks to this amazing guy right here who's going to talk about the future

00:12:04.500 --> 00:12:09.580
package just in the very next talk, so you all should stick around.

00:12:09.580 --> 00:12:15.380
Future works interoperably with foreach through the do future parallel adapter package, as

00:12:15.380 --> 00:12:21.219
do a number of other older parallel adapters that are listed there.

00:12:21.219 --> 00:12:26.260
Before this talk, I went and updated some that I've been neglecting for a while.

00:12:26.340 --> 00:12:30.979
The do-Redis and do-MPI, MPI and Redis backends for foreach are recently updated, and they're

00:12:30.979 --> 00:12:35.859
either on CRAN now or they're kind of pending into CRAN.

00:12:35.859 --> 00:12:41.299
And I started writing, kind of hacking together a guide to explain the internals of foreach

00:12:41.299 --> 00:12:45.580
to prospective parallel adapter authors.

00:12:45.580 --> 00:12:50.380
If you want to write your own parallel adapter to connect to your super-duper fancy whatever

00:12:50.380 --> 00:12:54.059
multi-GPU computer thing, you can do that, and there's a little guide there that helps

00:12:54.059 --> 00:12:59.140
walk you through how to dot the i's and cross the t's.

00:12:59.140 --> 00:13:06.539
Now I have to say I believe that this is a vitally important addition to the R software

00:13:06.539 --> 00:13:07.539
ecosystem.

00:13:07.539 --> 00:13:12.619
It really fills a gap, or it filled back in 2009 when we introduced it.

00:13:12.619 --> 00:13:19.340
It filled a gap that was really missing in R, and it's been very important.

00:13:19.340 --> 00:13:22.739
That's why I've tried to support it a little bit in a limited capacity here and there over

00:13:22.739 --> 00:13:23.739
the years.

00:13:23.739 --> 00:13:25.460
But you don't have to take my word for that.

00:13:25.460 --> 00:13:32.179
All you need to do is go on CRAN and look at the foreach page, and you can see all of

00:13:32.179 --> 00:13:37.580
these R packages that either depend explicitly or implicitly on foreach, and there's a lot

00:13:37.580 --> 00:13:38.580
of them.

00:13:38.580 --> 00:13:42.179
So there's a huge impact from this software.

00:13:42.179 --> 00:13:47.820
And that really makes me quite happy, because as some of you know...

00:13:47.820 --> 00:13:51.900
So we lost Steve last summer, he passed away, sadly.

00:13:51.900 --> 00:13:52.900
But he didn't, right?

00:13:52.900 --> 00:14:01.580
His ideas were as vital today to the R software ecosystem and spawning new work by new people

00:14:01.580 --> 00:14:04.739
as they were 10 years ago.

00:14:04.739 --> 00:14:10.500
So I think it's a testament to Steve's vision how important this work was.

00:14:10.500 --> 00:14:15.020
And this has been kind of a weird lightning introduction to an abstraction layer for parallel

00:14:15.020 --> 00:14:16.020
computing.

00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:19.820
I know I didn't go very deep into things, but I'm going to conclude this talk because

00:14:19.820 --> 00:14:22.979
I don't want to burden you with all of these super technical details.

00:14:22.979 --> 00:14:25.580
I'll leave that to Henrik.

00:14:25.580 --> 00:14:30.619
But I'd like to conclude the talk in kind of a weird, characteristically weird way.

00:14:30.619 --> 00:14:36.419
I'll paraphrase the great labor organizer and folk singer, Steve was also into folk

00:14:36.419 --> 00:14:38.739
music, Joe Hill.

00:14:38.739 --> 00:14:42.140
And on Joe's deathbed, he said, don't mourn, don't mourn my passing.

00:14:42.140 --> 00:14:43.140
Parallelized.

00:14:43.140 --> 00:14:47.619
Well, he didn't say parallelized, but Steve would have said parallelized.

00:14:47.619 --> 00:14:48.619
That's all I have for you.

