00:15:12.619 --> 00:15:17.299
So as the author of this package, I'm kind of curious about your answer.

00:15:17.299 --> 00:15:21.380
What do you think about the fir package as the combination of purr and future?

00:15:21.380 --> 00:15:23.140
Yeah, I think so.

00:15:23.140 --> 00:15:29.059
So the functional concepts, I mean, you can see me, I mentioned in Haskell, right?

00:15:29.059 --> 00:15:35.419
So having side effect free operations whenever possible that are promoted by things like

00:15:35.419 --> 00:15:39.580
the purr package are important.

00:15:39.580 --> 00:15:44.700
And they're in fact essential for embarrassingly parallel style map reduce computation that

00:15:44.700 --> 00:15:47.280
we get with future and with foreach.

00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:49.440
So I think it's a natural fit, actually.

00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:53.000
That's really what I have to say about it.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:54.000
One other question here.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.960
So this is just kind of technical, but how do we assign the number of cores to be used?

00:15:57.960 --> 00:16:01.200
Yeah, that's up to the parallel adapter code.

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:02.200
I mean, that's the point.

00:16:02.200 --> 00:16:04.239
At runtime, the user can make a decision.

00:16:04.239 --> 00:16:08.919
So if you're just using the R's native parallel package, you would supply a number.

00:16:08.919 --> 00:16:14.039
When you say register, I had that slide up there that said register do parallel.

00:16:14.039 --> 00:16:17.400
If you just put a number in there, that's the number of cores it's going to use.

00:16:17.400 --> 00:16:18.400
And that, of course, depends.

00:16:18.400 --> 00:16:21.479
If you're using an MPI back end, you've got a different convention.

00:16:21.479 --> 00:16:25.280
Or if you're using Redis or one of these other job queuing systems or whatever, they all

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:30.080
have slightly different conventions with dealing how the work is going to be run.

00:16:30.080 --> 00:16:31.080
Great.

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:35.520
So a couple more just popped in.

00:16:35.520 --> 00:16:38.599
Are there any recommendations about debugging when using parallel computing?

00:16:38.599 --> 00:16:41.039
Oh, that's a great question, actually.

00:16:41.039 --> 00:16:42.520
It's challenging, right?

00:16:43.039 --> 00:16:48.280
Parallel computing in general is nightmarishly complicated to debug.

00:16:48.280 --> 00:16:59.280
And yeah, in both the future work and in 4-H, there are various tricks that you can use

00:16:59.280 --> 00:17:01.000
to help debug your code.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:06.959
There's an option in 4-H to stop on the first error that's encountered on any worker process

00:17:06.959 --> 00:17:09.839
anywhere and throw that error in the R session.

00:17:09.839 --> 00:17:10.839
That's its default.

00:17:10.839 --> 00:17:13.680
But you can also just pass the errors as they come.

00:17:13.680 --> 00:17:17.959
So if you're getting lots of errors in your loop iterations, you can just see all of them

00:17:17.959 --> 00:17:19.640
to see what's happening.

00:17:19.640 --> 00:17:24.520
And you can also, this is probably not advisable, but you can also ignore errors.

00:17:24.520 --> 00:17:33.079
Depending on the back ends, the kind of adapter packages, the ones that work with the standard

00:17:33.079 --> 00:17:36.239
are parallel package and MC packages.

00:17:36.239 --> 00:17:38.520
They don't do so well at debugging.

00:17:39.040 --> 00:17:45.839
But some of the other parallel adapters have provisions in them for logging and maintaining

00:17:45.839 --> 00:17:48.479
logs to just regular R connections.

00:17:48.479 --> 00:17:57.359
So you can direct logs to files on the back end workers and inspect those after.

00:17:57.359 --> 00:18:01.359
Or if you have the ability to look at standard error, standard out, you can actually look

00:18:01.359 --> 00:18:04.239
at those as it's running on the other workers, too, to help debug.

00:18:04.239 --> 00:18:05.959
But it's still tricky.

00:18:06.199 --> 00:18:08.439
I'm sure this guy's going to have a lot more to say about that.

00:18:08.439 --> 00:18:09.439
Do you have more to say about it, Henrik?

00:18:09.439 --> 00:18:10.439
I don't know.

00:18:10.439 --> 00:18:11.439
It's hard, right?

00:18:11.439 --> 00:18:12.439
It's hard.

00:18:12.439 --> 00:18:13.439
I'm sorry.

00:18:13.439 --> 00:18:14.760
