00:18:18.719 --> 00:18:19.719
So I had a question.

00:18:19.719 --> 00:18:22.079
And if Max Kuhn is in here, I'm sure he'd be proud of me for asking.

00:18:22.079 --> 00:18:23.079
Yeah.

00:18:23.079 --> 00:18:24.079
There's Max.

00:18:24.079 --> 00:18:28.719
So he and I are really interested in getting messages kind of back in real time.

00:18:28.719 --> 00:18:32.520
Like any warnings or error messages coming back in real time from your workers.

00:18:32.520 --> 00:18:34.760
Is that even possible, depending on...

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:36.880
Well, I don't know about future.

00:18:36.880 --> 00:18:41.680
In 4-H, you can throw an error, and that's coming back in real time if you pass the errors

00:18:41.680 --> 00:18:42.680
through, right?

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:48.079
So that would be the only way to do that right now on any...

00:18:48.079 --> 00:18:51.520
For each in an abstract way.

00:18:51.520 --> 00:18:54.839
Like warnings and messages, maybe, where it's still continuing to run?

00:18:54.839 --> 00:18:56.640
Like that didn't stop the worker?

00:18:56.640 --> 00:18:57.640
Yeah.

00:18:57.640 --> 00:18:58.640
That's a great question.

00:18:58.640 --> 00:18:59.640
And I don't know of any facility for doing that.

00:18:59.640 --> 00:19:00.640
That would be...

00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:05.839
You'd need some extra communication channel off the main channel to send that information

00:19:05.839 --> 00:19:06.839
through.

00:19:06.839 --> 00:19:10.920
You could do it through files, but you may not have access to files.

00:19:10.920 --> 00:19:14.160
If they're running on another planet, maybe you can't get those, right?

00:19:14.160 --> 00:19:15.160
So I don't know.

00:19:15.160 --> 00:19:17.160
